[normal]&#xa0;[bold]How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also improving the environment? [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Needs to be 
[normal]recognised
[normal] that investment needs to be directed to the whole high
[normal]way networks as the majority of trips start and end on local highways;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The needs of other road users such as bus and coach does not appear to have much regard
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recognition of some form of segregation for pedestrians and cyclist on these routes needs to be m
[normal]ade
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The policies set out within the Command Paper addresses largely regional traffic, focusing on cars and HGVs in particular. The policy also makes reference to “future proofing” the strategic network for cycling. The policy however does not reference to
[normal] or provide any identified investment in the local road network, of which responsibility lies with Local Authorities. It needs to be 
[normal]recognised
[normal] that the vast majority of trips either start or end on these 
[normal]roads,
[normal] and that investment needs to also be directe
[normal]d towards supporting maintenance of the rest of the highway network, including associated bridges and other related infrastructure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The policy does not provide much information regarding other road users, in particular short-bus trips and long-distance co
[normal]ach routes which may also 
[normal]utilise
[normal] the strategic road network as modes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In addition, as these roads generally operate at high speed (50mph or higher) it is accepted that the roads need to be as safe as possible. This is reflected within the command paper t
[normal]o some extent for vehicles and future proofing for cyclists, but little reference is made regarding the potential risk for pedestrian and rights of way related casualties that can occur on the strategic network, in particular at uncontrolled level crossing
[normal]s over dual carriageways for rights of way. Due to both vehicular speeds and high risk of fatalities, some form of segregation may be required where possible for hazardous locations, which should be identified within the route based strategies, in particul
[normal]ar at locations where high KSI accidents occur.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]By making the best use of the existing highway network through use of selective junction improvements and removing bottlenecks, the policy has the potential to 
[normal]improve
[normal] the environment by mitigating traffic c
[normal]ongestion and 
[normal]minimising
[normal] the need for the provision of entirely new construction.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes? [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The form proposed here is similar to that of the rail industry which has been show
[normal]n to work
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The role of Park and Ride should be 
[normal]recognised
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Long terms planning of altern
[normal]ative modes such as rail lines should not be detrimentally affected by highways infrastructure proposals
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The policy need to link with the growth at sea and airports
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The p
[normal]olicy for roads follows a similar policy process for that of rail, with a long term strategy based on five year funding rounds, developed alongside smaller 
[normal]Route Based Strategies, which mirrors a similar method of Control Periods and Route 
[normal]Utilisation
[normal] Stra
[normal]tegies published by Network Rail. This form of planning has been shown to work within the rail industry, and should potentially work for the development of the highways network.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.6
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]One of the most direct links to other transport modes is for that of Park and
[normal] Ride schemes, both bus and rail orientated. The 
[normal]siting
[normal] of 
[normal]a
[normal] effective Park and ride site will help reduce congestion within towns and cities, and will most likely require being sited next to the strategic highway network to be effective.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.7
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]An additional in
[normal]teraction exists relating to the crossing of other transport infrastructure, including rail and canals. Significant planning is required to ensure that any future reinstatement of a rail line for instance is not detrimental and pushed up in cost through th
[normal]e development of a new road for instance. In addition, the maintenance or replacement of bridges and removal of level crossings require coordination between both parties to ensure that both modes see an advantage and not cause unnecessary maintenance liabi
[normal]lity on one mode.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.8
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Finally, the policy needs to link into the proposed growth of both airports and ports, both for the effective and efficient handling of freight and passengers to access these facilities. 
